<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-316-948  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 316 948.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 29 1989 v6 n21 p64(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MSP systems yield pay off. (marketing and sales productivity)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MarketingSalesAutomationBusiness.andO;Person:    Moriarty, Rowland (addresses, essays, lectures); Swartz, Gordon(addresses, essays, lectures).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>''In the rush to automate, the marketing and sales function is the nextfrontier,'' according to an article titled ''Automation To Boost Sales andMarketing'' in the January/February 1989 issue of the Harvard BusinessReview.andM;Authors Rowland Moriarty, an associate professor of business administrationat the Harvard Business School in Cambridge, Mass., and Gordon Swartz, aresearch associate there, cite case studies that indicate that marketing andsales productivity (MSP) systems can increase sales by as much as 30 percent.andM;For instance, at an electronics company with $7 billion in sales and 500salespeople, automation cost $2.5 million and was paid back in less than ayear by a 33 percent sales increase, a 31 percent sales-force productivityincrease and a 40 percent drop in sales-force attrition.andM;The article describes MSP systems, tells how they aid productivity anddescribes their use as a management tool.andP;  It suggests that early adopters ofMSP systems erected impressive competitive barriers, and it offers thefollowing advice for installation:andM;Clarify the scale of the project.andM;Concentrate on tasks that can add value for the customer.andM;Account for hidden costs and intangible benefits (expect to spend between$4,000 and $7,000 per person for hardware and software).andM;Make any tests realistic.andM;Pinpoint the roles of those selecting, designing and operating the system.andM;Modify the technology and the organization to support the system.andM;$</TEXT></DOC>